{"title":"Hybrid Instance-aware Temporal Fusion for Online Video Instance Segmentation","domain":"CV","seeds":[{"problem":"Online video instance segmentation struggles to leverage temporal context effectively: prior online methods either fuse frames only at the pixel level or at the instance level via detection-and-crop RoIs, leading to incomplete, biased frame-to-frame communications and heavy per-frame instance matching.","method":"Represent each frame with a hybrid pair of a global instance code (slot-based latent L×D capturing class and mask cues in an order-aware fashion) and CNN feature maps, and perform cropping-free temporal fusion via hybrid attentions. Intra-frame attention links code and pixels with code-to-code (c2c), code-to-pixel (c2p), and pixel-to-code (p2c) to build instance-aware features. Inter-frame attention fuses temporal information across adjacent frames using c2c&c2p to update target codes from reference codes/features and p2c to adjust pixel features, repeating intra- and inter-frame layers alternately within the backbone. This unified attention eliminates RoI cropping and enables instance-level aggregation directly from global context, yielding large gains (e.g., 41.3 mAP on YouTube-VIS 2019 with ResNet-50)."},{"problem":"Maintaining consistent instance identities online typically requires explicit frame-wise matching with handcrafted cues, which is brittle and computationally costly.","method":"Make the instance code order-aware and enforce cross-frame slot consistency during training with an assignment loss that jointly matches class and mask similarity across current and previous frames (t and t−1) to retain slot order. At inference, assign identities directly by slot indices for non-empty predictions, with a simple IoU>0.5 fallback when slots shift, thus removing complex matching and post-processing. This matching-free identity association, enabled by learned slot consistency, achieves state-of-the-art performance on YouTube-VIS 2019/2021 (41.3/35.8 mAP)."}]}
